<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>1. The case deals with the classic tension between, on the one hand, a vendor's disclosure obligations and, on the other hand, a purchaser's duty to do due diligence and the principle of <EM>caveat emptor</EM> or buyer beware.</P>
<P>2. The appellant vendor of residential real estate in Vancouver did not disclose to the respondent purchaser the fact of her son in law's murder on the front lawn of the subject property. The respondent purchaser learned of the the murder, which had occurred 2 years before the scheduled closing of the transaction and as a result of that discovery she refused to complete the transaction.</P>
<P>3. The learned trial judge determined that the fact of the murder was not a latent defect requiring disclosure by the vendor to the purchaser but he did conclude that the failure of the vendor to disclose the fact of the death to the purchaser in response to the question posed by the purchaser; &ldquo;why are you selling the property?&rdquo; constituted a fraudulent misrepresentation.</P>
<P>4. The vendor's response to that question was truthful but incomplete.</P>
<P>5. The first substantive issue raised by this appeal deals with the question of whether a misrepresentation by omission can arise in circumstances where a subjective consideration (in this case the death of the son in law) is not disclosed by the representee to the representor. The appellant vendor says that it cannot.</P>
<P>6. The second substantive issue raised by this appeal, in the alternative, is whether the representation by omission, if found to be false and material, was made fraudulently or negligently. The appellant vendor says that it was made negligently and the respondent purchaser was not entitled to repudiate the contract but rather only pursue a remedy in damages.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>7. This case arises out of the collapsed 2009 sale of a residential property located at XXXXXXXXXX in the Shaughnessy neighbourhood of Vancouver. (the &ldquo;Property&rdquo;)</P>
<P>8. The facts of the case are unusual in that the respondent, Feng Yun Shao<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ms. Shao had her name legally changed to Amy Barsha Washington in 2011 but she was referred to as Ms. Shao throughout the trial.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (the &ldquo;Purchaser&rdquo;) repudiated the agreement by which she was to purchase the Property from the appellant, Mei Zhen Wang (the &ldquo;Vendor&rdquo;), after learning that a person had been fatally shot in front of the Property about two years prior to the transaction.</P>
<P>9. The person who was killed was the Vendor's son-in-law, Hong Chao (Raymond) Huang (&ldquo;Mr. Huang&rdquo;). Mr. Huang died on XXXXXXXXXX and his assailant remains unknown. Mr. Huang was married to one of the Vendor's daughters, Gui Ying (Winnie) Yuan (&ldquo;Ms. Yuan&rdquo;).
<P1>RFJ, paras 33, 25</P1></P>
<P>10. At the time of trial, the Purchaser was an 84-year-old resident of Guanzhou, China. She has not had any formal education in her lifetime. She speaks Cantonese and is able to write her name in Chinese characters, but is otherwise illiterate.
<P1>RFJ para. 16.</P1></P>
<P>11. For most of the time relevant to this case, the Vendor was in China and, due to that fact and her illiteracy, Ms. Yuan assisted her with the sale of the Property pursuant to a power of attorney.
<P1>RFJ, paras 16, 32, 43</P1></P>
<P>12. At the time of trial the Purchaser was 50 years old. The Purchaser was born and educated in China, where she obtained a Master's Degree in Economics Management. She is now a Canadian citizen. The Purchaser's first language is Mandarin. At the time of the transaction, she spoke little English.
<P1>RFJ paras. 26, 28.</P1></P>
<P>13. The Property was purchased on behalf of the Vendor in 2003. When the Property was purchased, Ms. Yuan, Mr. Huang, their two children, and Ms. Yuan's older sister all lived at the Property together. The Vendor and her husband later joined them in 2004. The Vendor and her husband then returned to China in 2007.
<P1>RFJ at para 19, 21</P1></P>
<P>14. On XXXXXXXXXX an unknown assailant shot Mr. Huang to death outside of the Property.
<P1>RFJ, para. 33</P1></P>
<P>15. In December, 2007 the Vendor's granddaughter, Samantha, was asked to leave her private school, West Point Grey Academy. Samantha transferred to a public school in the area, Lord Kitchener. Ms. Yuan wanted her daughter to attend a private school where she would have a better opportunity to learn and speak English than she did at Lord Kitchener, a school attended by many Chinese students. In February 2008, Samantha passed the entry examination for Collingwood, a private school located in West Vancouver. She was to start at Collingwood in September 2008.
<P1>RFJ, paras. 36, 37</P1></P>
<P>16. In April of 2008 and in anticipation of Samantha attending Collingwood School, Ms. Yuan purchased a condominium in West Vancouver so that she and her family could live close to her daughter's new school.
<P1>RFJ, para. 36</P1></P>
<P>17. Ms. Yuan and her family remained at the Property until the end of Samantha's school year at Lord Kitchener in June 2008, and lived there intermittently from the months of April until the end of June. In sum, Ms. Yuan and her family resided at the Property for approximately eight months following the death of Mr. Huang.
<P1>RFJ para. 40</P1></P>
<P>18. On June 30, 2008 the Property was first listed for sale with Raymond Leung. After December 30, 2008 it was taken off the market for several months. The Property was then listed for sale with Julia Lau and Matthew Yee of Sutton Group&mdash;West Coast Realty from June 15 to December 30, 2009.
<P1>RFJ, paras 44, 46</P1></P>
<P>19. Ms. Yuan and Ms. Lau met in early June 2009 to discuss listing the property. Ms. Yuan informed Ms. Lau that her husband had been killed on the street in front of the Property. Ms. Yuan asked Ms. Lau whether it was necessary to disclose the death of Mr. Huang to prospective purchasers. Ms. Lau told Ms. Yuan that she would have to speak with her manager about whether it was necessary to disclose Mr. Huang's death.
<P1>RFJ, para 100</P1></P>
<P>20. Ms. Lau, as the listing agent, worked with another realtor, Matthew Yee (&ldquo;Mr. Yee&rdquo;), who acted as the showing agent. Ms. Lau asked Mr. Yee to find out from their manager whether it was necessary to disclose the death of Mr. Huang to prospective purchasers. Mr. Yee made an inquiry of his manager by email and on June 30, 2009 he sent an email to Ms. Lau setting out his understanding of the advice he received from the manager.
<P1>RFJ, para 101, 102</P1></P>
<P>21. Mr. Yee was advised by his manager that unless a prospective purchaser specifically inquired about a death, he did not have to disclose Mr. Huang's death. Mr. Yee was also advised by the manager that he and Ms. Lau should not express any opinion to the Vendor about disclosure of the death, and that they should recommend that she obtain her own legal advice.
<P1>RFJ, para 106</P1></P>
<P>22. Ms. Lau told Ms. Yuan that her manager had advised her that she need not disclose the death of Mr. Huang unless a buyer or buyer's agent asked about deaths on or near the property. She recommended to Ms. Yuan that she seek legal advice regarding the disclosure of Mr. Huang's death to prospective purchasers. Ms. Yuan did not seek independent legal advice regarding disclosure of the death.
<P1>RFJ, para 107</P1>
<P1>Transcript of examination in chief of Chi Yuen Lau p 345, qs 35 to 41</P1></P>
<P>23. Ms. Lau testified that when she told Ms. Yuan that she would disclose the death only if a purchaser made a specific inquiry, Ms. Yuan agreed with her approach.
<P1>RFJ, para 109</P1></P>
<P>24. Ms. Yuan, the Vendor, Ms. Lau and Mr. Yee all gave evidence that neither the Vendor nor Ms. Yuan instructed the realtors not to disclose Mr. Huang's death.
<P1>RFJ, para 110</P1></P>
<P>25. Ms. Yuan told both Ms. Lau and Mr. Yee that she was selling the property because her daughter would be attending a school in West Vancouver. She did not mention any other reason for the sale.
<P1>RFJ, para 104</P1></P>
<P>26. The Vendor was present in Vancouver on June 15, 2009 when she signed the multiple listing contract and property disclosure statement with Ms. Lau. Otherwise Ms. Yuan handled all discussions with Ms. Lau regarding the listing. The learned trial judge determined that the Vendor did not instruct either Ms. Lau or Mr. Yee how to answer if a buyer asked why she was selling the property.
<P1>RFJ, para 47, 50</P1></P>
<P>27. In her examination for discovery, The Vendor acknowledged that, after the death of her son-in-law, she was concerned about the safety of her two daughters and her grandchildren, who continued to reside at the Property. The Vendor remained in Guangzhou, China and was not residing at the Property at or around the time of the death.
<P1>RFJ, para 53, 45, 21</P1></P>
<P>28. The learned trial judge found that the death of Mr. Huang was one of the reasons that the Vendor wished to sell the Property. Her other reasons for selling the Property were that she wished to make her permanent home in Guangzhou and that Ms. Yuan intended to move to West Vancouver to be near her daughter's new school.
<P1>RFJ, para 58</P1></P>
<P>29. The contract of purchase and sale at issue is dated September 3, 2009 (the &ldquo;Contract&rdquo;). Pursuant to the Contract, The Vendor agreed to sell and The Purchaser agreed to buy the Property for the sum of $6,138,000. The completion date of the Contract was November 17, 2009.
<P1>RFJ, para 60 AB, p 9</P1></P>
<P>30. The Contract was entered into nearly two years following the date of the death of Mr. Huang.</P>
<P>31. By September 25, 2009, the Purchaser had removed all of the conditions in the Contract that were for her benefit and had paid a deposit totalling $300,000 (the &ldquo;Deposit&rdquo;).
<P1>RFJ para. 126</P1></P>
<P>32. On September 30, 2009, the Purchaser learned through a friend, that a death had occurred at the front entrance to the Property. The Purchaser then asked her husband to do a Google search of the Property. He found and showed to her a newspaper article describing the fatal shooting of a person alleged to be a gangster in front of the Property. The Purchaser acknowledged that she knew nothing about Mr. Huang beyond what she read in the news report that her husband had found and translated to Mandarin for her, using the translation function on his computer. Following her discovery of the death, the Purchaser refused to complete the Contract on the basis that the death was not disclosed to her by the Vendor or her agents.
<P1>RFJ para. 127, 130</P1></P>
<P>33. The learned trial judge found that when the Purchaser &ldquo;learned of the unsolved murder of Raymond Huang in front of the Property, she feared for her own safety, and the safety of her family.&rdquo; The Purchaser's particular concern was that she &ldquo;feared that the unknown perpetrator might return and mistake her children for members of Mr. Huang's family.&rdquo;
<P1>RFJ, paras 131, 190</P1></P>
<P>34. The Purchaser purchased other multi-million dollar homes on the west side of Vancouver at around the same time the Contract was to complete in November, 2009. The Purchaser bought a property at XXXXXXXXXX, (the &ldquo;Marine Drive Property&rdquo;), which completed on November 17, 2009. This was the same date that the Purchaser was supposed to complete the purchase of the Property. The purchase price was approximately $6.88 or $6.9 million.
<P1>Transcript of cross-examination of Feng Yun Shao p 520, qs 46 to 47, p 521, qs 40 to 46</P1></P>
<P>35. The Purchaser also bought another property at XXXXXXXXXX, (the &ldquo;Angus Drive Property&rdquo;) for $5.8 million. The Purchaser entered into the contracts to buy the Marine Drive Property and the Angus Drive Property in October 2009. Both properties were registered around November 17, 2009.
<P1>Transcript of cross-examination of Feng Yun Shao p 522, qs 28&ndash;31, p 525, qs 26&ndash;41</P1></P>
<P>36. Following the collapse of the Contract, the Vendor ultimately sold the Property to another buyer for the price of $5,500,000 in February 2010. This action ensued.
<P1>RFJ, para 3</P1>
<P1>AB, p 28</P1></P>
<P>37. At trial the Vendor sought damages from the Purchaser in the amount of $638,000 representing the difference between the Contract price and the subsequent sale price to the other buyer.
<P1>RFJ, para 4</P1></P>
<P>38. The Purchaser defended and counterlaimed on the basis that she was entitled to repudiate the Contract because the death was not disclosed to her. The Purchaser submitted that the Vendor was under an obligation to disclose the death of Mr. Huang on two grounds: (1) the death was a material latent defect in the Property; and (2) the death ought to have been disclosed when the Purchaser's agent asked the Vendor's agent the only question she had at the time: Why was Ms. Wang selling the Property? The answer given by the Vendor's agent was that the Vendor's granddaughter was changing schools. The Purchaser submitted that by omitting the death as a reason for selling the Property, the Vendor made a fraudulent or negligent misrepresentation.
<P1>RFJ, paras 5, 6</P1></P>
<P>39. Following a 14-day trial of this matter, the learned trial judge held that the Purchaser failed to establish that the Vendor was obliged to disclose the death of Mr. Huang as a latent defect.
<P1>RFJ para. 195.</P1></P>
<P>40. The learned trial judge concluded that the death of Mr. Huang was not a latent defect rendering the Property dangerous or uninhabitable and, accordingly, it was not a fact requiring disclosure by the Vendor. The death was not related to the physical or intrinsic qualities of the Property nor was it a defect or imperfection in respect of the Property or premises itself, or any measurable condition or quality of the Property.
<P1>RFJ paras. 191-192.</P1></P>
<P>41. The learned trial judge also concluded that even if the death was a defect, it was a patent, rather than a latent defect, which was capable of discovery by a purchaser making reasonable inquiries about the Property.
<P1>RFJ para. 194.</P1></P>
<P>42. However, with respect to the Purchaser's claim of fraudulent or negligent misrepresentation, the learned trial judge held that the Purchaser had established that she was induced to enter into the Contract by a fraudulent misrepresentation.
<P1>RFJ para. 221.</P1></P>
<P>43. The learned trial judge found that the Vendor made a false representation when she indicated, through her real estate agent, that her reason for selling the Property was that her granddaughter was changing schools, (the &ldquo;Representation&rdquo;) The learned trial judge found that this answer, while true on its face, was incomplete in that it concealed the fact that the granddaughter changed schools as an ultimate consequence of Mr. Huang's death, and that the death was a factor in the Vendor's decision to sell the Property.
<P1>RFJ paras. 202-203.</P1></P>
<P>44. The learned trial judge concluded that the death of Mr. Huang was a reason for selling the Property because the granddaughter would not have changed schools but for the murder of Mr. Huang.
<P1>RFJ, para. 208.</P1></P>
<P>45. In the result, the Purchaser's counterclaim was allowed and the Vendor's claim was dismissed. The Purchaser was granted rescission of the Contract and judgment for return of the Deposit, together with accrued interest, and consequential damages of $4,040.44.
<P1>RFJ, paras 221&ndash;226</P1></P>
<P>46. The Purchaser did not lead any evidence respecting damages, if any, that she would have suffered had she completed the Contract and pursued a remedy in damages.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ERRORS IN JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>47. The learned trial judge erred in concluding that by failing to disclose the death of Mr. Huang the Vendor had made a fraudulent misrepresentation which entitled the Purchaser to repudiate the Contract.</P>
<P><BOLD>48.</BOLD> In the alternative, if the death was material to the Purchaser's decision to enter into the Contract, the learned trial judge erred in finding that the representation was fraudulent rather than negligent.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>First Ground of Appeal:</UNDER> The learned trial judge erred in concluding that by failing to disclose the death of Mr. Huang the Vendor had made a fraudulent misrepresentation which entitled the Purchaser to repudiate the Contract.</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Standard of Review</EM></TI>
<P>49. Matters of fact or mixed fact and law are to be judged according to the standard of &ldquo;palpable and overriding error&rdquo; unless a question of law can be readily extracted.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Duty to Disclose</EM></TI>
<P>50. The learned trial judge correctly concluded that the Vendor was not obliged to disclose the death of Mr. Huang as a latent defect.
<P1>RFJ, para 195</P1></P>
<P>51. The learned trial judge found that &ldquo;Raymond Huang's death was not a defect or imperfection in respect of the property itself, or any measureable condition or quality of the property&rdquo; and &ldquo;even if the death was a defect, it was a patent, rather than a latent defect, which the vendor was not obliged to disclose to the buyer. Mr. Huang's death was a matter capable of discovery by a purchaser making reasonable inquiries about the property.&rdquo;
<P1>RFJ, paras 192, 194</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Fraudulent Misrepresentation</EM></TI>
<P>52. The test for fraudulent misrepresentation was correctly set out by the learned trial judge. In order to succeed in her claim the Purchaser was obliged to prove:
<P1>1) The Vendor's real estate agent made a representation of fact to the Purchaser regarding her reason for selling;</P1>
<P1>2) The representation made about the reason for selling was false in fact;</P1>
<P1>3) The vendor knew the representation was false when it was made;</P1>
<P1>4) The Vendor intended the Purchaser to act on the representation;</P1>
<P1>5) The Purchaser was induced to enter into contract in reliance upon the false representation and thereby suffered a detriment</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Callaway</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 189</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Van Beek v. Dodd</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1639</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>; RFJ, para 196</P1></P>
<P>53. The standard of proof for fraudulent misrepresentation is assessed on a balance of probabilities, having due regard to the seriousness of the allegation of deceit. Fraud requires a high standard with evidence that is clear and convincing proof of the elements of fraud, including the mental element. The &ldquo;mental element&rdquo; of a fraudulent misrepresentation is the intent to deceive.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ban v. Keleher</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1132</CITE><PARANUM>119</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Van Beek v. Dodd</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> at para 43</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Anderson v. British Columbia (Securities Commission)</SOC><CITE>2004 BCCA 7</CITE><PARANUM>29</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>a.</EM></N><TI>The Vendor's real estate agent made a representation of fact regarding the Vendor's reason for selling</TI>
<P>54. The learned trial judge found that Mr. Yee informed the Purchaser that the Vendor's reason for selling the Property was the granddaughter's change of school. The Vendor takes no issue with this.
<P1>RFJ, para 123</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>b.</EM></N><TI>The Vendor's representation regarding the reason for selling the Property was false in fact.</TI>
<P>55. The learned trial judge found that while the Representation was true on its face, it was a false representation because it was incomplete.</P>
<P>56. The Vendor accepts that if the disclosure of the death of Mr. Huang is a material fact that induced the Purchaser to enter the Contract, then the Representation was false in fact. The issue of the materiality of the Representation will be dealt with more fully later in this factum.</P>
<P>57. If this Court accepts the Vendor's later submission below that the Representation was not a material fact, then the conclusion of the learned trial judge that the Representation was &lsquo;calculated to conceal&rsquo; the death is legally irrelevant. The fact that the Representation did not fully encompass all of the Vendor's reasons for selling the Property is also irrelevant because there was no duty to disclose. The Purchaser did not ask and the Vendor did not say that the Representation reflected the only reason that the Vendor wished to sell the Property. It is respectfully submitted that in the absence of a duty to disclose or the determination that the Representation constituted a material fact, caveat emptor applies.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>c.</EM></N><TI>The Vendor knew the representation was false when it was made</TI>
<P>58. The learned trial judge found that Ms. Yuan knew that her daughter would not have changed schools but for the murder of Mr. Huang. Without question, the death of Mr. Huang was the first event leading to the granddaughter's change of schools. The change of schools was precipitated by the fact that the granddaughter had been required to withdraw from West Point Grey academy following the death of her father. Ms. Yuan and her family resided at the Property for 8 months until their move to West Vancouver to accommodate the granddaughter's new school.
<P1>RFJ, para 37, 40</P1>
<P1>Transcript of re-examination of Gui Ying Yuan, p 310</P1></P>
<P>59. As the Vendor truthfully disclosed that the reason for the sale of the Property was the granddaughter's change of schools, the imposition of a duty upon the Vendor to disclose all of the facts leading to the change of schools runs contrary to the well-established doctrine of <EM>caveat emptor</EM>. Absent a positive duty to disclose a fact or the determination that a fact is material to the contemplated transaction (in this case, the Contract), the obligation to engage in reasonable inquiry remains with the Purchaser.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Knight v. Dionne</SOC><CITE>[2006] QJ No. 3671</CITE><COURTJUR>Ct Qu CivD SmCl</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Cresswell Investments Ltd v. Pavone</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 1069</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>d.</EM></N><TI>The Vendor intended the Purchaser to act on the representation</TI>
<P>60. The learned trial judge found that Ms. Yuan informed the realtors of the Vendor's reason for selling; Ms. Yuan knew that the realtors would convey the representation to any prospective purchasers; and that Ms. Yuan intended that any purchasers would believe the truth of the statement.
<P1>RFJ, para 213</P1></P>
<P>61. The learned trial judge further concluded that the representation was &ldquo;calculated to conceal Mr. Huang's death as a reason for the plaintiff's decision to sell the property.&rdquo;
<P1>RFJ para 217</P1></P>
<P>62. It is submitted that that the learned trial judge made a palpable and overriding error in concluding that Ms. Yuan had the requisite intent to deceive, an essential element of a claim of fraudulent misrepresentation.
<P1>RFJ, para 197</P1></P>
<P>63. Ms. Yuan disclosed to and sought advice from the Vendor's realtors concerning her duty to disclose Mr. Huang's death to prospective purchasers. She was advised by the realtors that she had no duty to disclose the death of Mr. Huang unless specifically asked about it. She was further advised to seek legal advice on the issue. She was told by the real estate agents that they would only disclose the death of Mr. Huang if asked about it. Ms. Yuan agreed with this approach. This evidence, which was uncontradicted and accepted by the learned trial judge, vitiates the conclusion that the Vendor had a clear intent to deceive, such that it would meet the high standard of proof for fraud.
<P1>RFJ, para 208, 100, 109</P1>
<P1>AB, p 1</P1>
<P1>Transcript of examination in chief of Chi Yuen Lau p 345, qs 35 to 41</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>e.</EM></N><TI>The Purchaser was induced to enter into contract in reliance upon the false representation and thereby suffered a detriment</TI>
<P>64. On the fifth and final element, the learned trial judge found that the Purchaser relied on the representation and was induced thereby to enter into the Contract. The learned trial judge concluded that the representation was material to the Purchaser in her decision to enter into the Contract and that &ldquo;materiality&rdquo; is a subjective consideration in the mind of the Purchaser.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Battrum v. MacKenzie Estate</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1285</CITE><PARANUM>24-25</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1>RFJ, para 214</P1></P>
<P>65. It is essential that a misrepresentation be &lsquo;material&rdquo; in its nature and constitute a fact essential to the decision to enter into the transaction. A misrepresentation will be &ldquo;material&rdquo;, if it influences and induces a party to enter a transaction and affects or goes to its very essence and substance.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>C.R.F. Holdings Ltd v Fundy Chemical International Ltd</SOC><CITE>[1982] 2 WWR 35</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 8</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Van Beek v. Dodd</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> at para 71</P1></P>
<P>66. While the materiality of the Representation to the Purchaser's decision to enter into the Contract was viewed through the subjective lens of the Purchaser there remained, it is submitted, a concomitant duty upon the Purchaser to advise the Vendor of that subjectively determined material consideration.
<P1>RFJ, para 158</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Knight v Dionne</SOC><CITE>[2006] QJ No. 3671</CITE><COURTJUR>Ct Qu CivD SmCl</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>1784773 Ont. Inc v. K-W Labour Association et al</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 5401</CITE><PARANUM>13, 14</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2014 ONCA 288</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>67. Put simply, had the Purchaser advised the Vendor that it was important for her to know whether any resident of the Property had been involved in criminal activity or had been murdered at the Property and if the Vendor had then failed to disclose the death of Mr. Huang, this case would not be before the court. The failure to disclose the death would clearly have been a fraudulent misrepresentation.</P>
<P>68. The learned trial judge was alive to the issue of the subjective factors that might influence a buyer of real estate. He found that other buyers might not have been concerned about the death of Mr. Huang. For those other buyers, the fact of the death of Mr. Huang would not have been a &ldquo;material&rdquo; consideration in their decision to make an offer to buy the Property.</P>
<P>69. In the context of the issue of latent defects the learned trial judge identified the impossible challenges that such a subjective obligation to disclose would impose upon Vendors. Such an obligation would render the doctrine of Caveat Emptor essentially meaningless.
<P1>RFJ at para 162, 193</P1></P>
<P>70. In the context of his fraudulent misrepresentation analysis however, it is respectfully submitted that the learned trial judge fell into error by imposing on the Vendor the obligation to determine the Purchaser's subjective view of the facts &ldquo;material&rdquo; to the decision to enter the Contract.</P>
<P>71. It is submitted that the obligation to disclose a subjective consideration as material must rest with the party for whom the subjective consideration is relevant. The Vendor has found no cases where a party has been found liable for a fraudulent misrepresentation by omission in circumstances where the innocent party did not ask a specific question to the representing party, <UNDER>regarding their subjective concerns</UNDER>.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Knight v. Dionne</SOC><CITE>[2006] QJ No. 3671</CITE><COURTJUR>Ct Qu CivD SmCl</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Battrum v. MacKenzie Estate</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1285</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>72. As stated by Fridman on the issue of the materiality of representation:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N>(d)</N><TI>Intent that plaintiff should act</TI>
<P>The misrepresentation must be material. In other words, it must be as to something which was intended to induce the other party to enter into a contract. For example, if there is a misrepresentation as to the identity of a contracting party, it will not be effective, in the legal sense, even if false, unless it was known to the person making the misrepresentation that the identity of the party with whom he was contracting was important to the victim of the misrepresentation, and it was intended to influence what he did. ...</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE>
<P1>Fridman, G.H.L., The Law of Contract in Canada, 6<SUP>th</SUP> ed (Toronto: Thomson Carswell 2011) at 289-290</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Second Ground of Appeal: In the alternative, if the death was material to the Purchaser's decision to enter into the Contract, the learned trial judge erred in finding that the representation was fraudulent rather than negligent.</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Negligent Misrepresentation</EM></TI>
<P>73. The test for negligent misrepresentation is well established:
<P1>1) There must be a duty of care based on a &ldquo;special relationship&rdquo; between the Vendor and the Purchaser;</P1>
<P1>2) The representation in question must be untrue, inaccurate, or misleading;</P1>
<P1>3) The Vendor must have acted negligently in making said misrepresentation;</P1>
<P1>4) The Purchaser must have relied, in a reasonable manner, on said negligent misrepresentation; and</P1>
<P1>5) The reliance must have been detrimental to the Purchaser in the sense that damages resulted.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>The Queen v. Cognos Inc.</SOC><CITE>[1993] 1 SCR 87</CITE><PAGENUM>at 110</PAGENUM></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Cresswell Investments Ltd. v. Pavone</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 1069</CITE><PARANUM>29</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Callaway</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> at para 34</P1></P>
<P>74. If a plaintiff is successful in establishing negligent misrepresentation they are entitled only to the remedy of damages. Rescission is only available in cases of fraudulent misrepresentation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Lamontagne v. Anderson</SOC><CITE>2005 BCSC 343</CITE><PARANUM>64</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>75. The test for negligent misrepresentation requires the purchaser to have <EM>reasonably</EM> relied on the misrepresentation, whereas fraudulent misrepresentation requires only that the purchaser was induced to enter the contract in reliance upon the representation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Callaway</SOC></CASEREF>, supra at para 51</P1></P>
<P>76. In the case of <CASEREF><SOC>Ban v. Keleher</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1132</CITE></CASEREF> the seller was concerned about potential contamination on his property which caused him to seek advice on the matter from his realtor. When completing the property disclosure form, the seller failed to make a connection between a question about the environmental condition of the property and two notices he had received regarding potential contamination of the property. The seller contended that he genuinely believed that he was answering the question truthfully and that he lacked the intention for the buyers to act on the representation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ban v. Keleher</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1132</CITE><PARANUM>24, 30</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>77. The court in <CASEREF><SOC>Ban v. Keleher</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> held that the seller was negligent in making the false representation but there was no &ldquo;clear and convincing proof&rdquo; that the representation was advanced &ldquo;for the purpose of deceiving the purchaser.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ban v. Keleher</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> at para 52</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>No Fraudulent Intent</EM></TI>
<P>78. If the learned trial judge was correct in his determination that the Representation was false by omission and that it was material to the decision of the Purchaser to enter into the Contract, the Vendor submits that the Representation was made negligently rather than fraudulently. It is submitted that the learned trial judge made a palpable and overriding error in his determination that the Vendor possessed a fraudulent intent to deceive.</P>
<P>79. As discussed in paragraph 53 of this factum, fraud requires a high standard of proof, particularly in regard to the mental element of intent to deceive.</P>
<P>80. It is submitted that the undisputed facts of this case, as found by the learned trial judge, vitiate any intent on the part of the Vendor to deceive the Purchaser.</P>
<P>81. Ms. Yuan did not actively seek to hide the fact of the death of Mr. Huang. Rather, she disclosed the fact of Mr. Huang's death to the Vendor's realtors and sought their advice concerning the circumstances in which she would be required to disclose the death.
<P1>RFJ at para 208</P1></P>
<P>82. Mr. Yee (the Vendor's showing realtor) sought the advice of his manager respecting this question. He communicated the answer to Ms. Lau (the Vendor's listing realtor) by an email of June 30, 2009. Ms. Lau then told Ms. Yuan that there was no duty to disclose the death of Mr. Huang to prospective purchasers but that Ms. Yuan should seek legal advice on the matter.
<P1>RFJ, para 101, 106, 108, 107</P1></P>
<P>83. Ms. Lau then told Ms. Yuan that she would disclose the death if a purchaser made a specific inquiry about a death at or near the Property. Ms. Yuan agreed with her approach.
<P1>RFJ, para 107, 109, 110</P1></P>
<P>84. Neither the Vendor nor Ms. Yuan instructed the realtors not to disclose Mr. Huang's death. They all understood that the death of Mr. Huang would be disclosed if a specific inquiry was made.
<P1>RFJ, para 110</P1></P>
<P>85. It is the case that Ms. Yuan did not seek legal advice despite the recommendation of the realtors. It is respectfully submitted, however, that having received the advice of the realtors that the death of Mr. Huang need not be disclosed, the Representation could not possibly have been made with fraudulent intent. At worst, the Representation was made negligently.
<P1>RFJ, para 107</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Damages as remedy</EM></TI>
<P>86. If the Vendor is liable for a negligent misrepresentation, the remedy therefore is damages. The Purchaser was not entitled to repudiate the Contract. She was obliged to complete the Contract and pursue her remedy in damages.</P>
<P>87. On the facts of the case at bar, despite pleading negligent misrepresentation the Purchaser led no evidence respecting the damages that she would have suffered as a consequence of the negligent misrepresentation. One might speculate that such damages would have included the transaction costs incurred in reselling the property. The Purchaser led no evidence on these damages nor did she prove that there would have been any diminution in value on a resale of the Property as a result of the negligent misrepresentation.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>88. The Vendor seeks an Order allowing the appeal and dismissing the counter claim.</P>
<P>89. The Vendor seeks a further order setting aside the award of damages made against the Vendor in the amount of $4,040.44</P>
<P>90. The Vendor seeks a further Order granting judgement to the Vendor for damages for the Purchaser's wrongful repudiation of the Contract in the amount of $638,000 or, in the alternative, judgment for $300,000 representing the amount of the deposit paid by the Purchaser on account of the Contract.</P>
<P>91. Costs of the appeal and of the trial in the court below.</P>
