<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>A. This appeal is without merit. The trial judge instructed himself correctly in law, exercised his discretion judicially with respect to findings of credibility and made no palpable or overriding errors. The appellant has not demonstrated any reviewable error.</P>
<P>B. This case concerns the collapse sale of a luxury house in Vancouver. The Purchaser asked the Vendor why she wanted to sell her beautiful home in Shaughnessy and she replied that her granddaughter was changing schools to West Vancouver to better her English.</P>
<P>C. The Vendor omitted to tell the Purchaser that her granddaughter had been asked by West Point Grey Academy to leave the school following the killing of her father at the front gate of the Property. The &ldquo;murder&rdquo; remains unsolved to this day.</P>
<P>D. The appellant says that this case is about the tension between the doctrine of <EM>caveat emptor</EM> and the duty of a vendor's disclosure obligations. It is not. The doctrine is inapplicable in face of misrepresentation.</P>
<P>E. Relying on the half-truth of the Vendor and ignorant of that which she had concealed as to the reason why she was selling her house in Shaughnessy, the Purchaser agreed to buy it. When she discovered the truth, she refused to complete the sale.</P>
<P>F. The trial judge found that the Vendor's concealment of the killing and true reason for the child's change of schools made her representation about why she wanted to sell, a deliberate deceitful statement intended to induce the Purchaser to buy the Property.</P>
<P>G. The trial judge found that the respondent (plaintiff by counterclaim) proved on a balance of probabilities the requisite elements of fraudulent misrepresentation, granting rescission and damages for the cost of legal advice. He did not entertain negligent misrepresentation, although pleaded.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Background</TI>
<P>1. The respondent does not take issue with the appellant's statement of facts but wishes to state its own version of the relevant facts with references to testimony contained in the transcript.</P>
<P>2. In 2003 the appellant's daughter Gui Ying Yuan (&ldquo;Winnie&rdquo;), a Canadian citizen acting on behalf of her mother, purchased a residence at XXXXXXXXXX in the Shaughnessy neighbourhood of the City of Vancouver, British Columbia for $3,700,000. Title of the Property was transferred to her mother after she immigrated to Canada in 2004.
<P1>RFJ paras. 17&ndash;20</P1></P>
<P>3. In 2007 the appellant returned permanently to China, leaving power of attorney with Winnie. Following her return to China, Winnie's husband Mr. Raymond Huang, an alleged member of a criminal organisation known as the Big Circle Boys was shot to death at the front gate of the Property on XXXXXXXXXX. The killing remains unsolved.
<P1>RFJ paras. 21, 33, 35, 41</P1></P>
<P>4. Following Mr. Huang's death, his daughter was asked to leave West Point Grey Academy, the private school she was attending. She moved to a public school in Vancouver, and then to a private school in West Vancouver.
<P1>RFJ para. 37</P1></P>
<P>5. In 2008 the Vendor decided to sell the Property. On June 30, 2008, Winnie listed the Property with Mr. Raymond Leung, the realtor who had sold it to her mother. Mr. Leung, a discredited witness, testified that Mr. Raymond Huang signed the offer to purchase the Property in 2003.
<P1>RFJ para. 44 T, page 478 l. 31 to l. 36, page 479 l. 39 to l. 42</P1></P>
<P>6. The Property did not sell in 2008. After the listing expired, the Vendor waited six months and then on June 15, 2009, re-listed the Property for sale with another realtor, Julia Lau who worked with a partner, Matthew Yee. On August 4, 2009, the listing price was reduced from $7,690.0 00 to $6,980.000.
<P1>RFJ paras. 32, 46, 47</P1></P>
<P>7. After Winnie told her realtors about her husband's death the realtors sought their managers' advice with respect to the duty to disclose it. The managers were divided about the duty to disclose. One advised disclosing everything and &ldquo;when in doubt disclose!&rdquo;
<P1>RFJ paras. 100, 102, 105</P1>
<P1>Appellant's Appeal Record (AR), pages 1, 3, 7</P1>
<P1>T, p. 110, ll. 5&ndash;10, p. 394, l. 30-36, p. 396, ll. 5&ndash;37, p. 402 l. 45 to p. 404, l. 1, p. 593, ll. 13&ndash;38</P1></P>
<P>8. On this issue, the realtors advised Winnie to get independent legal advice which she failed to do. At trial, Winnie denied that she had received such advice, but the judge preferred the evidence of the realtors.
<P1>RFJ paras. 106,107</P1>
<P1>T, p. 112, ll 11&ndash;31, p.396 ll 9&ndash;13, page 593, and ll. 13&ndash;38</P1></P>
<P>9. The plan adopted by Winnie and her realtors was that the death would only be disclosed if a buyer posed a specific question regarding it.
<P1>RFJ paras. 106,109, 110</P1>
<P1>T, p. 344, II. 35&ndash;39, 345 II 8&ndash;15, 35&ndash;41, p. 594, ll. 38&ndash;46</P1></P>
<P>10. On September 3, 2009, the respondent, offered to purchase the Property for $6,138,000, with completion date being set for November 17, 2009.
<P1>RFJ para. 2, AB, pp. 9&ndash;20</P1></P>
<P>11. Following the removal of conditions of the Contract on or about September 30, 2009, the Purchaser found out about the killing at the Property. She immediately contacted her realtor who confirmed the killing, whereupon she instructed her realtor to inform the Vendor that she would not complete the Contract.
<P1>RFJ paras. 127&ndash;129, 131 and T, p. 500, ll. 41&ndash;46, p. 501, ll. 34&ndash;39</P1></P>
<P>12. The Purchaser had instructed her realtor to ask the Vendor why she was selling such a beautiful house. The Vendor's realtors replied that Winnie's daughter was changing schools to West Vancouver to better her English. There was no mention of the shooting of Mr. Huang. The Purchaser asked no further questions.
<P1>RFJ paras. 103, 104, 123, 124</P1>
<P1>T, p. 509, ll. 36 to p. 510, l.1, p. 510, ll. 14&ndash;31, p. 599 ll. 39&ndash;41, p. 624, l. 26 to p.625 l.14</P1></P>
<P>13. Matthew Yee, one of the Vendor's realtors testified that he told Bowei Deng, the Purchaser's realtor that Winnie's daughter, &ldquo;did not have enough chance to practice English&rdquo;, while living at the Property. Ms. Deng testified that Mr. Yee told her that there were fewer Chinese people in West Vancouver, so it was &ldquo;beneficial&rdquo; for Winnie's daughter to move there, &ldquo;in terms of education and language.&rdquo;
