<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ISSUES ON APPEAL</TI>
<P>A. Did the respondent (plaintiff by counterclaim) prove on a balance of probabilities the requisite elements of fraudulent misrepresentation?</P>
<P>B. When does a half-truth constitute fraudulent misrepresentation?</P>
<P>C. Did the misrepresentation and omission constitute negligent rather than fraudulent misrepresentation?</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>Did the respondent prove on a balance of probabilities the constituent elements of fraudulent misrepresentation?</TI>
<P>64. The central issue, in this case, is whether the Vendor's concealment from the Purchaser of the unsolved killing of her son-in-law in 2007 at the front gate of the Property constituted fraudulent misrepresentation entitling the Purchaser to rescission and damages for legal advice.</P>
<P>65. The appellant says that this case is about the tension between the doctrine of <EM>caveat emptor</EM> and the duty of a vendor's disclosure obligations. It is not. The doctrine is inapplicable in face of misrepresentation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>McCluskie v. Reynolds</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 5384</CITE><COURTJUR>BC SC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1998] 65 B.C.L.R. (3d) 191</CITE><PARANUM>46-47</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, (Bennett J., as she then was).</P1></P>
<P>66. For example, this exception to the doctrine was applied in <CASEREF><SOC>Aldred v. Colbeck</SOC></CASEREF>, where the seller failed to disclose to the buyer the presence of an underground storage tank.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Aldred v. Colbeck</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 57 (CanLII)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2010 BCSC 57</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>67. The appellant concedes that the trial judge correctly instructed himself on the test for fraudulent misrepresentation. The trial judge stated at paragraph 196:
<QUOTE><P>In order to succeed on a claim of fraudulent misrepresentation the defendant must establish the following elements:
<P1>1) the vendor made a representation of fact to the purchaser;</P1>
<P1>2) the representation was false in fact;</P1>
<P1>3) the vendor knew the representation was false when it was made, or made the false representation recklessly, not knowing if it was true or false;</P1>
<P1>4) the vendor intended the purchaser to act on the representation;</P1>
<P1>5) the purchaser was induced to enter into contract in reliance upon the false representation and thereby suffered a detriment.</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1>See <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Callaway</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 189</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM></CASEREF>; and <CASEREF><SOC>Van Beek v. Dodd</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1639</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>RFJ para. 196, Appellant's factum, para. 52</P1></P>
<P>68. The trial judge then carefully applied the requisite elements of fraudulent misrepresentation to the facts.
<P1>RFJ paras. 202&ndash;212</P1></P>
<P>69. The trial judge made adverse findings of credibility against the Vendor and her daughter Winnie about being less than candid about the circumstances of the killing of Mr. Huang and the reasons for selling the Property.
<P1>RFJ paras. 209 to 211</P1></P>
<P>70. The appellant contends that the standard of proof for fraud requires a,
<QUOTE><P>...high standard with evidence that is clear and convincing proof of the elements of fraud, including the mental element.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Appellant's factum, para. 53</P1></P>
<P>71. There is only one standard of proof in a civil case, proof on a balance of probabilities. There are no degrees of probability within the civil standard.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>F. H. v. McDougall</SOC><CITE>[2008] 3 SCR 41</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2008 SCC 53 (CanLII)</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>72. The trial judge applied the correct standard of proof.</P>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Fraudulent Misrepresentation</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK5><TI>First</TI>
<P>73. With respect to the first element, the judge found that when asked, the Vendor through her realtors made incomplete statements about the reason for selling the Property, concealing the fact that the granddaughter was asked to leave her school as a result of the shooting of her father and that the death was a factor in deciding to sell the Property.
<P1>RFJ, paras. 202, 203</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI>Second</TI>
<P>74. On the second element, the judge found that the Purchaser established on a balance of probabilities, that the representation by the Vendor's realtors as to the reason for selling the Property was a false representation by omission, citing Fenlon J., as she then was, in <CASEREF><SOC>Battrum v MacKenzie Estate</SOC><CITE>2010, BCSC 1285</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>, quoting S.M. Waddams that,
<QUOTE><P>...an incomplete representation may amount to an actionable falsehood.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>RFJ, paras. 204&ndash;206</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI>Third</TI>
<P>75. For the third element, the trial judge found that the Vendor had no intention of disclosing the killing of Mr. Huang unless obliged to do so. The judge found that Winnie knew that the representation was untrue because she acknowledged that her child would not have changed schools to West Vancouver but for the killing of her husband [208]. Additionally, the judge had difficulty giving credit to Winnie's evidence in her interrogatories that her husband had died by accident [209] or not remembering whether she discussed the shooting with Mr. Leung or whether she told him that the killing was the reason for selling [210].
<P1>RFJ paras. 207&ndash;211</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI>Fourth</TI>
<P>76. As to the fourth element, requiring the Purchaser to establish that the Vendor intended her to act on the false representation, the trial judge found that the Vendor's daughter, Winnie,
<QUOTE><P>...intended that any prospective purchaser who made the inquiry would believe the truth of the statement, and would accept that the vendor had no other reason for selling the Property.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>RFJ para. 213</P1></P>
<P>77. A finding of intent to deceive is a finding of fact.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>C.R. F. Holdings Ltd. v. Fundy Chemical International Limited</SOC><CITE>1981 CanLII 488</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1981] BCJ No 1633</CITE><PARANUM>4, 5</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>78. <EM>CRF</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> is instructive. On appeal, Craig J.A. accepted the facts as set out at trial by Taylor. J., as he then was. This court upheld the trial judgment finding a vendor liable for fraudulent misrepresentation for concealing the truth about waste on his property. The vendor told the purchaser that waste slag would make &ldquo;excellent fill&rdquo; while concealing that it was radioactive.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>C.R.F. Holdings Ltd. v. Fundy Chemical International Limited</SOC><CITE>1980 CanLII 586</CITE><COURTJUR>BCSC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><YEAR>1980-81</YEAR><CITE>14 C.C.L.T. 87</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>79. In <EM>CRF</EM>, the trial judge held that when the purchaser inquired about the waste slag, the vendor was bound to reveal that it was radioactive, a fact the vendor concealed from the purchaser. The concealment, Taylor J. found, was calculated to deceive the purchaser, and it did. The case is apposite to the case at bar.
<P1><EM>CRF</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 4</P1></P>
<P>80. The appellant argues at para. 57 of its factum that the Purchaser was obliged to ask if the change of schools by the Vendor's granddaughter was the only reason for selling the Property. The trial judge correctly ruled that once the Purchaser asked the general question, she was entitled to an accurate, complete answer, not one that concealed the truth. The Purchaser was not required to ask anything further.
<P1>RFJ para. 217</P1></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><TI>Fifth</TI>
<P>81. Finally, the fifth element, the Purchaser must prove that the Vendor's false representation induced her to enter into the Contract to purchase the Property and that she acted on the false representation.</P>
<P>82. On this requirement, the judge once again referred to Fenlon J. in <EM>Battrum</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, and this court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Sidhu Estate v. Bains</SOC></CASEREF>,
<QUOTE><P>[214] Finally, to maintain her counterclaim for deceit, Ms. Shao, must establish that the plaintiff's false representation induced her to enter into the contract. In Battrum, Fenlon J. stated the test for this element at paras. 24 to 25:</P>
<P>24 The test of materiality of the representation and reliance on it is a subjective one; it is not a matter of asking whether a reasonable person would have relied on the representation, but whether this plaintiff relied upon it in the circumstances of this case.</P>
<P>25 Battrum was induced to enter into the investment in AOI by a number of factors. It is likely that the opportunity to make a large and quick profit was a greater inducement than the security afforded by the units held in trust, but the law does not require the misrepresentation to be the only or even the most significant reason for the plaintiff's action. As stated in George Spencer Bower, The Law of Actionable Misrepresentation, 3d ed. (London: Butterworths, 1974) at 139:</P>
<P>120 It is sufficient to prove that the representation was an inducing cause. It is not necessary to establish that it was the inducing cause. Whether, if a full disclosure of the truth had been made, the representee would or would not have altered his position in the manner in which he did, is a question to which the law does not require an answer. It is enough if a full and exact revelation of the material facts might have prevented him from doing so&mdash;if it would have &ldquo;given him pause&rdquo;. [Emphasis in original; footnote omitted.]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>In <CASEREF><SOC>Sidhu Estate v. Bains</SOC><CITE>[1996] 10 W.W.R. 590</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>25 B.C.L.R. (3d) 41</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, Finch J.A. (as he then was) stated the following at para. 36 (cited to W.W.R.):
<QUOTE><P>It is therefore sufficient in my view to found liability in deceit if the fraudulent representation is a material inducement upon which the representee relied, even if that representation is only one of several factors contributing to her decision.</P></QUOTE></P1>
<P1>RFJ, para. 214</P1></P>
<P>83. On this point, the appellant argues at paragraphs 59 and 71 of its factum that the Purchaser was obliged to ask the Vendor a specific question about whether there had been any criminal activity on the Property. There is no such duty on a purchaser to a vendor who conceals information. As stated by James LJ in <CASEREF><SOC>Re Arnold</SOC><YEAR>1880</YEAR><CITE>14 Chd 270</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 281</PAGENUM><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF>,
<QUOTE><P>If a man makes a description calculated to mislead, I do not think that is well for him to say, if you had been very careful you would have found out the blunder.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Spencer Bower &amp; Handley, Actionable Misrepresentation</EM>, Fifth edition, 2014, LexisNexis page 125, footnote 8</P1></P>
<P>84. As the learned authors, <EM>supra</EM>, state at page 124,
<QUOTE><P>The representee has no duty to be careful, suspicious or diligent in research when the misrepresentation was intended to put his mind at rest.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>85. The trial judge accepted the evidence of the Purchaser that along with other factors, she relied on the Vendor's (mis)representation regarding the reason for selling the Property.
<P1>RFJ para. 215</P1></P>
<P>86. Once the Purchaser established that the misrepresentation might reasonably lead to her claimed loss, the onus shifted to the Vendor to prove that the misrepresentation was not in fact relied on. The question of onus was at issue in <EM>Shidhu</EM> where Mr. Justice Finch, as he then was, stated,
<QUOTE><P>I think the preferred view of the law in Canada is that once intention, materiality and causation of loss are proven, the burden of proving non-reliance shifts to the defendant.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Sidhu Estate v. Bains</SOC><CITE>1996 CanLII 3332</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>77 BCAC 116</CITE><PARANUM>42</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>87. The Vendor failed to discharge its onus of proving non-reliance.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><UNDER>Materiality</UNDER></TI>
<P>88. The appellant argues that the killing is not a material fact, therefore there was no obligation on the Vendor to disclose it. The appellant argues that the trial judge fell into error by,
<QUOTE><P>..imposing on the vendor the obligation to determine the purchaser's subjective view of the facts &ldquo;material&rdquo; to the decision to enter the Contract.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>Appellant's factum, para. 70</P1></P>
<P>89. The trial judge did not impose any such obligation on the appellant. Materiality is defined by the learned authors of <EM>Spencer Bower</EM> as,
<QUOTE><P>A representation is material when its tendency, or its natural and probable result, is to induce the representee to alter his position as he did. This is a question of fact.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Spencer Bower &amp; Handley</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, page 80</P1></P>
<P>90. Unlike insurance law, objective materiality is not required as an essential element of deceit. The learned authors point out that the 3<SUP>rd</SUP> edition of Bullen and Leake of 1881 does not contain any allegations of materiality in the pleading at a time when deficient pleading was fatal to an action. The view that materiality is an essential element in a cause of action for deceit has been rejected in Australia.
<P1><EM>Spence Bower</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, pp. 84-85</P1></P>
<P>91. In fraudulent misrepresentation, the representor defines the relevant facts. Materiality depends on the impact of the representation. If the representation induces, then its material, if it does not, it is not material. Materiality is,
<QUOTE><P>...simply persuasive evidence of intent to induce and actual inducement.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>Spence Bower</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, p. 85, footnote 9, RFJ, paras. 214, 217</P1></P>
<P>92. Here the trial judge found that the Vendor intended that any prospective purchaser would believe and act on the half-truth, namely that the Vendor had no other reason to sell the Property.
<P1>RFJ para. 213</P1></P>
<P>93. The judge found that the half-truth induced the Purchaser to enter into the Contract. The judge correctly instructed himself that the representation does not have to be the only reason, or even the most significant reason, citing <EM>Battrum</EM> and <EM>Sidhu</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>. The judge found that the Purchaser relied on the Vendor's representation regarding the reason for selling the Property.
<P1>RFJ paras. 216, 217</P1></P>
<P>94. The trial judge found that the representation induced the Purchaser to buy the Property, hence it was material. The appellant has not shown that the trial judge made any palpable or overriding error.</P>
<P>95. The trial judge must have reasoned that the omission about the killing might have reasonably deterred, or tended to deter the respondent from purchasing the Property. The judge drew a proper inference of fact in the circumstances of the case.
<P1>RFJ para. 217</P1>
<P1><EM>Spence Bower</EM>, p. 86. footnote 9</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>When does a half-truth constitute fraudulent misrepresentation?</TI>
<P>96. A half-truth may be a misrepresentation. There are many cases in Canada and England where it has been held that half-truths can amount to deceit. Taylor J. in <EM>CRF</EM> cited often quoted passages:
<QUOTE><P>16 The law with respect to deceit by half-truth has its foundation in the colourful dictum of Chamber, J., in <CASEREF><SOC>Trapp v. Lee</SOC><YEAR>1603</YEAR><CITE>127 E.R.</CITE></CASEREF> (at page 203) (sic <CASEREF><SOC>Tapp v Lee</SOC><CITE>1803 3 Bos &amp; P 367</CITE></CASEREF>):
<ITEM><P>An action on the case for deceit is an action well known to the law, and I cannot agree in the argument which has been used for the defendant, that such actions ought to be confined to representations which are literally false. Fraud may consist as well in the suppression of what is true, as in the representation of what is false. If a man, professing to answer a question, select those facts only which are likely to give a credit to the person of whom he speaks and keep back the rest, he is a more artful knave than he who tells a direct falsehood.</P></ITEM></P>
<P>In <CASEREF><SOC>Peek v. Gurney</SOC><YEAR>1673</YEAR><CITE>(sic 1873) L.R. 6 H.L. 377</CITE></CASEREF>, Lord Chelmsford observes (at pages 291-2) that while mere concealment will not suffice to give rise to a right of action in deceit, so that there must be &ldquo;something actively done to deceive [the other party] and draw him in to deal with the person withholding the truth from him&rdquo;, this may well be accomplished by a half-truth. He observes that half a truth will sometimes amount to a &ldquo;real falsehood&rdquo;, and may contain &ldquo;a positive misrepresentation&rdquo;. The law is summarized in Spencer-Bower and Turner on Actionable Misrepresentations (Third Edition at page 94) in this passage:
<ITEM><P>To state a thing which is true only with qualifications or additions is known to, but studiously with-held by, the representor is to say the thing which is not. Such a statement is a lie, and one of the most dangerous and insidious forms of lie.</P></ITEM></P>
<P>While it is true that in Canada the concept of fraudulent concealment by silence alone has not gained the acceptance which it has found in the United States law governing sale of land, <UNDER>the concept of deceit by incomplete disclosure which is here recognized may impose very similar obligations on a vendor who answers a prospective purchaser's questions.</UNDER></P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>CRF</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, (trial), at para. 16 (underlining added)</P1></P>
<P>97. In <EM>CRF</EM>, on appeal, Anderson J.A. (dissenting in part with respect to damages) referred to the following cases:
<QUOTE><P>51 In addition to the authorities referred to by the trial judge, I would make reference to several cases where it has been held that to knowingly represent only favourable aspects without disclosing the fact that those favourable aspects are substantially qualified by restrictions and unfavourable aspects, known to the person making the representation, amounts to fraud.</P>
<P>52 Firstly, I make reference to the judgment of Denning L. J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Curtis v. Chemical &amp; Dyeing Co.</SOC><CITE>[1951] 1 K.B. 805</CITE><PAGENUM>at 808-9</PAGENUM></CASEREF> as follows:
<ITEM><P>In my opinion any behaviour, by words or conduct, is sufficient to be a misrepresentation if it is such as to mislead the other party about the existence or extent of the exemption. If it conveys a false impression, that is enough. If the false impression is created knowingly, it is a fraudulent misrepresentation; if it is created unwittingly, it is an innocent misrepresentation; but either is sufficient to disentitle the creator of it to the benefit of the exemption.di In <CASEREF><SOC>Rex v. Kylsant</SOC></CASEREF> (Lord) it was held that a representation might be literally true but practically false, not because of what it said, but because of what it left unsaid; in short, because of what it implied.</P></ITEM></P>
<P>See also the judgment of Avory J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Rex v. Kylsant</SOC><CITE>[1932] 1 K.B. 442</CITE></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>53 In that case, the following comments were made:
<P1>(a) Sometimes a half-truth is no better than a downright falsehood. (p.446)...</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1><EM>CRF</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, BCCA, paras. 51&ndash;53</P1></P>
<P>98. The answer to the Purchaser's question, that the reason for selling the Property was because Winnie's daughter was changing schools to better her English, was false and misleading. The answer given by the Vendor assured the Purchaser and dispelled any need to ask further questions. The truth lay in the omission. Even silence may be actionable.
<P1><EM>Sidhu</EM>, supra, paras. 31, 32</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>Did the misrepresentation and omission constitute negligent rather than fraudulent misrepresentation?</TI>
<P>99. The appellant argues at paragraph 78 of its factum that the trial judge,
<QUOTE><P>...made a palpable and overriding error in his determination that the Vendor possessed a fraudulent intent to deceive.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>100. The trial judge's finding of intent to deceive is a finding of fact. The trial judge observed the witnesses at trial and made findings of credibility which support his decision on intent. Findings of credibility are delicate matters best left undisturbed by appellate courts.
<P1>RFJ paras. 10&ndash;15, 209 to 211</P1></P>
<P>101. In the seminal case on appellate standard of review, <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court once again stated that trial judges are in the best position to assess credibility,
<QUOTE><P>... We take the above comments of McLachlin J. to mean that, although the same high standard of deference applies to the entire range of factual determinations made by the trial judge, where a factual finding is grounded in an assessment of credibility of a witness, the overwhelming advantage of the trial judge in this area must be acknowledged. ...</P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33 (CanLII)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2002] 2 S.C.R. 235</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>102. The appellant in this case carefully planned her answer to the potential question about why she was selling the Property and how she would conceal the shooting. She acted with forethought and deliberation.
<P1>RFJ, paras. 100, 209, T, p. 345, ll. 35&ndash;41, p. 110. ll. 5&ndash;41, p. 111, ll. 19&ndash;31, p. 228, ll. 5&ndash;7, p. 235, ll. 2&ndash;4</P1></P>
<P>103. The appellant chose not to seek legal advice on the issue, at her own peril. She denied in cross-examination that her realtors advised her to do so. The judge did not believe her on this issue.
<P1>RFJ, p. 107, and T, p. 112, ll. 11&ndash;31</P1></P>
<P>104. The appellant did not answer the Purchaser's question truthfully. She was not careless in her answer. Her answer was not an innocent mistake. She did not hold an honest belief that it was true. These are all elements of negligent misrepresentation which are lacking in this case.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Queen v. Cognos Inc.</SOC><CITE>1993 CanLII 146</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1993] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>105. Secrecy is the badge of fraud. The appellant concealed the true reason for why she was selling the Property. The trial judge had evidence on which to make his finding of fraudulent intent, a finding of fact. The judge did not commit any error in law or make any findings of fact that can be said to be plainly wrong. The judge did not make any palpable or overriding error in finding intent of deceit on part of the appellant.</P>
<P>106. The trial judge did not consider negligent misrepresentation as it was obviated by the finding of deceit.</P>
<P>107. It is incumbent on the appellant to demonstrate an error on the part of the trial judge. It has not done so.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kondori v. New Country Appliances Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 164 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>110. The respondent seeks an Order that the appeal be dismissed.</P>
<P>Dated at the City of Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, this &ellip10;th of September 2018.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Wallace M. Wong</P>
<P>Counsel for the Respondent</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
